{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2014}} This article conserns [[LGBT history]] in the [[Nordic country]] of [[Denmark]].
==History== * 1668 - [[Nicholas Culpeper]] and Abdiah Cole publish [[Thomas Bartholin]]'s ''Anatomia''. Bartholin briefly mentions lesbianism in this book. He uses the phrases, ''confricatrices rubster'' and ''contemptus vivorum'', to describe female homosexuality. Bartholin cites historical examples of lesbianism, such as [[Sappho]], [[Philaenis]], and the [[Book of Romans]].<ref>{{cite book |first=Thomas |last=Bartholin |title=Bartholinus Anatomy made from the Precepts of his Father, and from the Observation of All Modern Anatomists, Together with his Own... |publisher=Culpeper and Cole |location=London |year=1668 |url=https://quod.lib.umich.edu/e/eebo/A31102.0001.001/1:4.34?rgn=div2;view=fulltext }}</ref> * '''1683'''&nbsp;– The [[Kingdom of Denmark]] criminalizes "relations against nature", making it punishable by death.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://denmarktodayblog.wordpress.com/2014/12/04/the-danish-lgbt/|title=DENMARK, PIONEER IN RIGHTS FOR THE LGBT|work=Denmark Today|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160209085634/https://denmarktodayblog.wordpress.com/2014/12/04/the-danish-lgbt/|archivedate=9 February 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref> * [[Homosexuality]] in [[Denmark]] was decriminalised in 1933.<ref name="History">{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-25927595 |title=Where is it illegal to be gay? |accessdate=23 February 2014 |work=BBC News}}</ref> * '''1948'''&nbsp;– "[[Danish National Association of Gays and Lesbians|Forbundet af 1948]]" ("League of 1948"), a homosexual group, is formed * 1976: Denmark equalizes the age of consent. * 1985: F-48 became the [[Danish National Association of Gays and Lesbians]] (''Landsforeningen for Bøsser og Lesbiske, Forbundet af 1948'' or ''LBL''). * 1989: Denmark is the first country in the world to enact [[registered partnership]] laws (like a [[civil union]]) for same-sex couples, with most of the same rights as marriage (excluding the right to adoption (until June 2010) and the right to marriage in a church); activists [[Axel and Eigil Axgil]] and 10 other Danish couples are unofficially married by Tom Ahlberg, the deputy mayor of [[Copenhagen]], in the [[Copenhagen City Hall|city hall]], accompanied by worldwide media attention. * 2010: Same-sex couple adoption legislation is passed. * 2012: [[Same-sex marriage in Denmark|Same-sex marriage]] is passed into law. * 2014: Denmark becomes the first European country to remove the Gender Identity Disorder diagnosis as a necessary requirement in the gender recognition process.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.lgbt-ep.eu/press-releases/denmark-becomes-europes-leading-country-on-legal-gender-recognition/|title=Denmark becomes Europe's leading country on legal gender recognition &#124; The European Parliament Intergroup on LGBTI Rights|date=2014-06-12|publisher=Lgbt-ep.eu|accessdate=2015-04-10}}</ref> * 2016: [[LGBT rights in Greenland|Greenland]] passes same-sex marriage. * 2017: Denmark becomes the first country in the world to officially remove transgender identities from its list of mental health disorders.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonblade.com/2017/01/04/denmark-no-longer-considers-transgender-people-mentally-ill/|title=Denmark no longer considers transgender people mentally ill|last=Lavers|first=Michael K.|date=|publisher=Washingtonblade.com|accessdate=2017-01-05}}</ref> [[Same-sex marriage in the Faroe Islands|Same-sex marriage]] is passed in the [[Faroe Islands]].
